<span class="MsoFootnoteReference"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt">[1]</span></span></a><span style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&nbsp;
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Christian Arab of Palestinian origin and Swiss citizenship, holding a
 doctorate in law from the University of Fribourg. Graduate in political
 sciences from the Graduate Institute of International Studies of Geneva.
 Responsible for Arab and Islamic law in the Swiss Institute of Comparative
 Law in Lausanne. He has written many books and articles on Arab and Islamic
 law besides more general works on the Middle East (see the list in:
<a href="http://go.to/samipage" style="text-decoration: underline; text-underline: single">
<span style="text-decoration: none">http://go.to/samipage</span></a>). This
 article constitutes a resume of his book published in French (Les Musulmans
 en Occident entre droits et devoirs, L‚ÄôHarmattan, Paris, 2002, 296 pages)
 and in English (</span><span style="font-size: 10pt">Muslims in the West
 caught between rights and duties: redefining the separation of Church and
 State, Shangri-La Publications, Warren Center (USA), 2002, 318 pages)</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt">.</span></div>
